					<div class="commentheading">On December 15, 2007 at 09:43 PM, Michael Chu said...</div>
					<div class="commentsubject">Subject: <span>Re: i am cooking two roasts for christmas?</span><br /></div>
					<div class="commentbody"><div class='commentquote'>guest wrote:<div class='commentquotebody'>I am getting a 9-rib roast for christmas, and i am going to cut it at 5 ribs and have a 4 rib left over. I am cutting it like this to fit it in the oven. My question is, do i cook both of the rib roasts the same amount of time as if it were a whole 9 rib roast or do i cook them as if i were cooking a 5 rib roast? Thank you</div></div><br />
It'll end up closer to the time it takes for a 4-5 rib roast than for a 9-rib roast due to the extra surface area on the two extra end pieces you are exposing. However, I've found that the total time for a 4-5 rib roast doesn't differ drastically from that of a 9-rib (which is what I've got in the oven right now).</div>
