					<div class="commentheading">On December 24, 2009 at 06:56 PM, Michael Chu said...</div>
					<div class="commentsubject">Subject: <span>Re: thermometer</span><br /></div>
					<div class="commentbody"><div class='commentquote'>neeki wrote:<div class='commentquotebody'>hey michael, where do you stick in the meat thermometer?  i know its supposed to go right into the center, but is there a place you like to place it in particular?  i feel kinda strange about poking a hole in my roast and am paranoid about juices leaking out.</div></div><br />
Just stick it in the middle. Look to see how long your probe is and check the diameter of our roast. Take note of where on the probe you should stop when shoving it in (it should go in about the same distance as the radius). Now find the mid point of the length of the roast and push that probe in. If you think of the roast as a cylinder, it should go in at the middle of the long side (not the caps). Don't worry about juices leaking out - it's just one small hole, there are plenty of juices in the roast.</div>
