					<hr size="1" noshade />
					<div class="commentheading">On December 23, 2010 at 06:38 PM, Dilbert said...</div>
					<div class="commentsubject"></div>
					<div class="commentbody">I would not put a dang decent slice of prime rib in a microwave for nuttin' - ever.<br />
<br />
lettuce as a 'cover' - interesting, not run across that 'technique'<br />
<br />
if you can get the slices completely thawed and thence to 'room temp' - a liberal drowning of hot a'jus will probably get you real close.<br />
<br />
the bottom line is pretty simple - doing the roast from scratch produces a chunk of meat hotter on the outside and cooler to the center.  difficult to replicate that effect precisely in a reheat situation without over cooking some/all portion of the roast - but if the meat was a good chunk to start with and properly roasting to second with, it's a good bet you'll get a sumptuous cut out of it.</div>
